\n\n==Other Rolling Stock==\nThe railway owns three rail mounted [[crane (railroad)|cranes]]: a 10T Grafton steam P-Way crane, a 15T Taylor Hubbard diesel P-Way Crane and an ex LMS 45T steam breakdown crane. Currently only the 15T Taylor Hubbard crane and the Grafton steam train are available for use.  Furthermore, there are a variety of wagons used by the civil engineering department, largely at either Oakworth of Ingrow West.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Rolling stock of the Keighley and Worth Valley Railway}}\n* [http://www.kwvr.co.uk/  Keighley and Worth Valley Railway website]\n* [http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org Ingrow Museum of Rail Travel \u2013 Vintage Carriages Trust]\n* [http://www.bahamas45596.co.uk Ingrow Loco Museum \u2013 Bahamas Locomotive Society]\n* [http://www.britishrailways1960.co.uk/NERS76.html  British Railways in 1960 \u2013 Keighley to Oxenhope]\n* [http://www.lyrtrust.org.uk/  Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Trust website]\n\n[[Category:Lists of locomotives and rolling stock preserved on heritage railways in England|Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]]\n[[Category:Keighley and Worth Valley Railway|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe '''Rolling stock of the Keighley and Worth Valley Railway''' is used on the preserved [[Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]], a {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=mid|-long|0}} branch line that served mills and villages in the [[Worth Valley]] and is now a [[heritage railway]] line in [[West Yorkshire]], England. It runs from [[Keighley]]<ref>{{coord|53.8671|-1.9003|display=inline|region:GB_scale:5000}}</ref> to [[Oxenhope]].<ref>{{Coord|53.81503|-1.9517|display=inline|region:GB_scale:5000}}</ref> It connects to the national rail network line at [[Keighley railway station]].\n\n==Steam locomotives==\n\n===Operational===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Type\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! Notes\n|-\n|No. 85\n|[[Taff Vale Railway O2 class]] {{whyte|0-6-2|T}}\n|[[File:A3_KWVR_Little_Engines_Gala_08I07I2017.jpg|175px]]\n|TVR lined black\n|<small>Number 85, along with other members of its class, was introduced to the [[Taff Vale Railway]] in 1899. At the grouping in 1923, the [[Great Western Railway]] received nine O2 class engines. They were all withdrawn during the 1920s, but No. 85 was bought by the Lambton Hetton & Joicey Colliery Co in [[Durham, England|Durham]], numbered 52. It continued to work at the Philadelphia depot at Houghton-le-Spring until 1968. Number 85 arrived at KWVR at the end of 1970, but although a major restoration was not completed until 2000, where it was restored to original Taff Vale Railway condition for the first time in preservation. The boiler ticket expired in September 2009 and its overhaul was started soon afterwards because of the locomotive's popularity and good condition.<ref name=\"P&P Spring 2011\">{{cite news|publisher=Push and Pull|date=1 December 2010|title=Standard '4' Locomotive Preservation Society}}</ref> The locomotive returned to service in February 2016 for the year's winter steam gala. Boiler ticket expires in 2026.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Winter Steam Gala|url=http://kwvr.co.uk/kwvr-news-items/2016-winter-steam-gala/|website=Keighley and Worth Valley Railway|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=25 February 2016}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|No. 5820 \"Big Jim\"\n|[[USATC S160 Class]]<br/>{{whyte|2-8-0}}\n|[[File:S160 5820 at Oxenhope.JPG|175px]]\n|USATC grey\n|<small>Built as works number 8758 by the [[Lima Locomotive Works|Lima]] company of America in 1945, No. 5820 was shipped to Britain and then almost immediately to France to help with the World War II war effort.<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p84\">{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=84}}</ref> After the war had ended, it went to Polish Railways where it was numbered Tr203.474<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p84\" /> and allocated to [[Katowice]] shed.</small>\n\n<small>During the 1970s, Polish steam was in decline while the British preservation movement was growing. No. 5820 was brought to Haworth in November 1977<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p84\" /> and became known as 'Big Jim'. It reverted to its [[USATC]] number the following summer and starred in '[[Yanks]]'.</small>\n\n<small>No. 5820 was withdrawn from service in 1992. After a heavy overhaul, the locomotive returned to service in early 2014 in inauthentic BR unlined black livery as No. 95820 before reverting to its more authentic guise as USATC Grey No. 5820. Boiler ticket expires in 2023.</small>\n|-\n|No. 41241\n|[[London Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] {{whyte|2-6-2|T}} [[LMS Class 2MT 2-6-2T|Class 2MT]]\n|[[File:Ivatt 2-6-2T 41241 at Keighley - geograph.org.uk - 1580038.jpg|175px]]\n|K&WVR Maroon.\n|<small>No. 41241 was built at [[Crewe Works]] in 1949 and from there went to [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] Green Park shed (71G).<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> After a few shorts spells at other sheds and transfer back to 71G, it was transferred to Wellington shed (84H) in October 1959. In 1964, No. 41241 was moved to [[Leamington Spa]] (2L), back to Wellington and to Wales, where it stayed at [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] (6H) and [[Croes Newydd]] (6C).<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> In 1965, No. 41241 went to [[Llandudno Junction railway station|Llandudno Junction]] shed (6G) for about 3 months before finally being transferred to [[Skipton]] (10G). It was withdrawn in December 1966, where it was taken under its own steam to its present home on the KWVR,<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> where it was destined to haul the re-opening special. Its boiler 'ticket' expired on 20 January 2013, and was withdrawn from service for its 10-year overhaul. During the engine's overhaul it required extensive firebox work amongst many other required tasks. It returned to traffic during the KWVR's 50th anniversary gala in June 2018.<ref>http://kwvr.co.uk/event/50th-anniversary-gala/2018-06-24/</ref> Boiler ticket expires in December 2027. </small>\n|-\n|No. 43924\n|[[Midland Railway 3835 Class]]<br/>{{whyte|0-6-0}}<br/>(LMS Class 4F)\n|[[File:British Railways Midland Region Class 4F 43924 Oxenhope.jpg|175px]]\n|BR unlined black with late crest\n|<small>Built in October 1920 at [[Derby Works]], it was allocated to Wellingborough where it was deployed on coal trains to London and return of empty wagons.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Allocated to Saltley Shed (21A) in March 1930; Gloucester Barnwood (22B) in July 1937; Bristol Barrow Road (82E) in September 1962; withdrawn in July 1965.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Sold and transferred to [[Woodham Brothers]] in October 1965. Became the first locomotive in September 1968 to leave Barry scrapyard and earned a reputation as a reliable KWVR performer until it was withdrawn from service in December 1987. 43924 re-entered revenue-earning passenger service in July 2011 for the first time in nearly 25 years after an extensive overhaul. Boiler ticket expires in 2021.</small>\n|-\n|No. [[LMS Jubilee Class 5596 Bahamas|45596]] \"Bahamas\"\n|LMS {{whyte|4-6-0}} [[LMS Jubilee Class|Class 5XP Jubilee]]\n|[[File:Bahamas reversing of Tyseley's turntable.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Lined Green with late crest.\n|<small>Built in January 1935, No. 5596 was named 'Bahamas' without ceremony on 8 June 1936.<ref name=\"KVWR Locos ATW\">p.24{{full citation needed|date=February 2013}}</ref> It ran with both Stanier {{convert|4000|gal|l}} and Fowler {{convert|3500|gal|l}} gallon tenders. It was renumbered to 45596 in 1948, in line with the rest of the BR renumbering at that time. In 1961, Bahamas was fitted with a double chimney.<ref name=\"KVWR Locos ATW\" /></small>\n\n<small>Bahamas was purchased by the Bahamas Locomotive Society in 1967 and, after a heavy overhaul at the Hunslet Railway Company in Leeds and a short period of storage, arrived at the Dinting Railway Centre in 1968.</small>\n\n<small>45596 returned to steam for the first time in over 21 years in September 2018 following a [[Network Rail]] standard overhaul at [[Tyseley Locomotive Works]]. Following running in and its light and loaded test runs the engine returned to the KWVR in Feb 2019.<ref>http://www.uksteam.info/tours/t19/t0205p.htm UK Steam timings for 45596's return to the KWVR</ref><ref>http://ingrowlocomuseum.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/45596-Press-Release.pdf Press release from the BLS regarding completion of overhaul</ref> Boiler ticket expires in December 2027.</small>\n|-\n|No. 75078\n|BR {{whyte|4-6-0}} [[BR Standard Class 4 4-6-0|Class 4MT]]\n|[[File:Standard Class 4MT 4-6-0 75078 3 (40735890451).jpg|175px]]\n|BR lined black with late crest\n|<small>No. 75078 was built at Swindon in 1956, one of 15 heading for the [[Southern Region of British Railways|Southern Region]].<ref>{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=45}}</ref> Initially based at Exmouth Junction (72A), it moved away to Basingstoke (70D) in May of that year. 75078 was fitted with a double chimney during overhaul in October 1961. In March 1963, it was moved to [[Nine Elms Locomotive Works|Nine Elms (70A)]], the main shed for [[London Waterloo]] and in May 1965, it was moved to [[Eastleigh Works#Locomotive Depot|Eastleigh (70D)]].</small>\n\n<small>No. 75078 was withdrawn in 1966,<ref>{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=46}}</ref> and sent to [[Woodham Brothers|Barry]] scrapyard in [[South Wales]] where it languished for five and a half years until it left to take up residence at the KWVR in 1972, where it has remained ever since.</small>\n\n<small>Returned to service in February 2015 after more than 16 years out of traffic.<ref>{{cite web |work=Keighley and Worth Valley Railway |url=http://news.kwvr.co.uk/2015/01/25/75078-passenger-duty-150124/ |title=First passenger 'turn' for BR Standard 75078 |publisher=Keighley & Worth Valley Railway|date=25 January 2015 |accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> Boiler ticket expires in 2024.</small>\n|-\n|No. 78022\n|BR {{whyte|2-6-0}} [[BR standard class 2 2-6-0|Class 2MT]]\n|[[File:Hugh llewelyn 78022 (7850847762).jpg|175px]]\n|BR Lined Green with early emblem\n|<small>Built at [[Darlington Works]] in 1954 and was allocated to Millhouses Depot in Sheffield. Its final allocation was Lostock Hall in Preston, where it was withdrawn from British Rail service in February 1967. 78022 was purchased in 1975 and, following an extensive restoration, was returned to service in 1993. It proved to be a popular locomotive, capable of handling most of the Worth Valley's trains. It was withdrawn for a ten-year overhaul at the end of 2000 and was moved to [[Oxenhope]] for display inside the museum.</small>\n\n<small>The engine was moved back to Haworth in May 2014 for preparations for overhaul, which started in early 2015 following the completion of 75078. The boiler was lifted out of the frames in March 2015 and the wheels removed the following year. On 22 May, it passed its steam test, giving it a new 10-year boiler ticket which expires on the same day in 2028. In June, its boiler was lifted back onto its frames. The engine returned to traffic in November 2018 after 18 years out of service, Boiler ticket expires in 2028.</small>\n|}\n\n===Currently elsewhere===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! History and Current Status\n|-\n|No. 752 (51456)\n|[[L&YR Class 23]] {{whyte|0-6-0|ST}}\n|[[File:LYR Aspinall 0-6-0ST No. 752 Rainhill 1980.jpg|175px]]\n|BR unlined black with early emblem\n|<small>Built in 1881 by [[Beyer Peacock]] as works number 1989 for the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] as a [[L&YR Class 25|class 25]] (similar to No. 957), it was rebuilt in its present form of an [[Saddle tank (locomotive)|0-6-0ST]] in 1896 at [[Horwich Works]].<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p72\">{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=72}}</ref> Now as a class 23, it was a common site on both local goods and shunting turns. It was allocated to [[Wigan]] locomotive shed in 1921 and remained there until it was disposed of by the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] in April 1937 (now numbered 11456) being loaned and then sold to the Blainscough Colliery Co Ltd, which was [[National Coal Board|nationalised]] in 1947. It ran on NCB metals until 1968.<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p72\" /></small>\n\n<small>It is now under the ownership of the Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Trust. Restoration was started in 1968 at the factory site of Yates Duxbury & Son Ltd in Heap Bridge near Bury, before moving to the KWVR in 1971. It is once again undergoing restoration, which is being undertaken at the [[East Lancashire Railway]]. Recently made first moves under own steam for 37 years in Oct 2019. The engine is presently outshopped in BR unlined black with the earlier BR crest and wearing the BR number 51456. \n\nAlthough authentic for the class no 752 never wore BR black or carried the BR number 51456 following sale from the LMS to what would later be the National Coal Board in 1937.</small>\n|-\n|No. 45212\n|LMS [[Black Five]] {{whyte|4-6-0}}\n|[[File:45212 Waiting in platform 3 at Keighley.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Lined Black with late crest.\n|<small>No. 5212 was built by [[Armstrong Whitworth]]'s [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] works, and entered traffic in November 1935, with its home being Bradford Low Moor (25F), where it was often tasked with working [[Pennines|Transpennine]] trains.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> In November 1947, No. 5212 moved to Fleetwood shed (24F), and in October of that year it was renumbered to become No. 45212.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> In October 1964, it was shedded at Carnforth (10A); moving in March 1965 to Speke Junction (8C); back to Carnforth in June 1965; to Carlisle Kingmoor (12A) in September 1965 and upon closure, to Lostock Hall (10D). No 45212 moved to the KWVR in October 1968.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/></small>\n\n<small>The locomotive returned to service in 2016 following an overhaul at [[Riley and Son|Ian Riley Engineering]] workshop in [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] on the [[East Lancashire Railway]], the overhaul being done to [[Network Rail]] standards. Boiler ticket expires in 2026.\n\n45212 is presently away from the K&WVR working railtours, it is presently located at [[Carnforth MPD]]\n|}\n\n===Undergoing overhaul===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! History and Current Status\n|-\n|No. 957\n|[[L&YR Class 25|Class 25 \"Ironclad\"]]<br/>0-6-0\n|[[File:Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway No. 957.jpg|175px]]\n|L&Y Lined Black.\n|<small>Designed by Barton Wright for the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] in 1875/6, No. 957 was delivered by [[Beyer Peacock]] in 1887.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\">{{cite book|last=Heavyside|first=Tom|title=Keighley & Worth Valley locomotives as they were|year=1996|publisher=Midland|location=Leicester|isbn=1-85780-050-8 |ref=harv }}{{page needed|date=April 2012}}</ref> It was on the books of Goole Shed at [[Railways Act 1921|grouping]], when it became LMS No. 12044; and it remained there until January 1950<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> when [[British Railways|British Rail]] moved it to [[Wakefield]] shed (25A).</small>\n\n<small>No. 957 was privately purchased from BR in 1959 and moved to KWVR in 1965 where it became famous for its role in ''[[The Railway Children (1970 film)|The Railway Children]]''. It was withdrawn from service in 1975 in need of a major overhaul and spent a significant amount of time on display in Oxenhope museum. The major overhaul was eventually started and 957 returned to service in 2001 wearing BR Black livery as No. 52044 before reverting to its L&Y guise of 957 a couple of years later. It was mainly used on summer vintage trains and during special events as well as the occasional normal passenger service. Its boiler certificate expired on 20 January 2013. Following a couple of years on display at Oxenhope, 957 moved back to Haworth in July 2016 with its overhaul now underway. It is aimed to have the locomotive operating again by 2020.</small>\n|-\n|No. 1054\n|[[LNWR Webb Coal Tank]]<br/>{{whyte|0-6-2|T}}\n|[[File:Rth LNWR 0-6-2T 1054 Haworth 300613 edited-2.jpg|175px]]\n|LNWR unlined black\n|<small>Built at [[Crewe Works]] in September 1888.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Built for freight work, these coal tanks were often used for local passenger trains, and some (including 1054) were fitted with [[Push\u2013pull train|push-pull]] equipment. From [[Railways Act 1921|grouping]], the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] numbered it No. 7799. It was withdrawn in January 1939,<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> although it was reinstated to traffic in December 1940 due to [[World War II]]. It was one of a fleet of 64 coal tanks passed from LMS to [[British Railways|BR]] ownership, when it was renumbered 58926 and it was shedded in locations as varied as Bangor, Patricroft, Manchester, Bletchley, Edge Hill, Liverpool and Shrewsbury.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> In the mid-1950s, the locomotive was loaned to the [[National Coal Board]], but had returned to British Rail by 1955. On its return, it was steamed only occasionally, predominantly for stand-by snow-plough duties until it was requested by the [[Stephenson Locomotive Society]] to double head a special train to mark the closure of the Abergavenny to Methyr route with 7F No. 49121. Bought by the former shedmaster of Bangor, Mr J. M. Dunn who restored it to LNWR condition.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> After a short stay at Hednesford, Staffordshire, it found itself donated to [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|The National Trust]] who later loaned it to the [[Dinting Railway Centre]] who put it back into running order for the [[Rainhill Trials#Rocket 150|Rocket 150]] celebrations in 1980.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> When the Dinting Railway Centre ceased to exist in 1990, 1054 moved to the KWVR. The general overhaul of No. 1054 was finished in late 2011. Running in took place over the winter and it is currently operational and used on vintage trains. \n\nFollowing the discovery of leaking tubes, the locomotive had its last steaming on 3 November 2019, before being withdrawn for a ten-yearly overhaul. The aim is to have the locomotive operational again for the centenary of the merging of the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway and the London and North Western Railway in 2022.</small>\n|-\n|No. 7069 \"Southwick\"\n|[[Robert Stephenson and Hawthorns]] {{whyte|0-4-0|T|C}}\n|\n|N/A\n|<small>Built in 1942. Undergoing overhaul at Ingrow West.</small>\n|-\n|No. 90733\n|[[British Rail|BR]] 2-8-0 [[WD class 8F 2-8-0|Austerity]]\n|[[File:WD Austerity 90733 Haworth Loco Yard.jpg|175px]]\n|BR unlined black with late crest\n|<small>Built at the [[Vulcan Foundry]] (No.5200), for the [[War Department (United Kingdom)|War Department]] (WD No. 79257), dispatched in January 1945. Shipped over to [[Netherlands Railways|NSR Netherlands]], No. 4464.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Limited history in the Netherlands, but allocated to Rietlanden at the beginning of 1949, before moving to [[Eindhoven]]. Sold to [[Statens J\u00e4rnv\u00e4gar|Swedish State Railways]] in 1953, moved to [[\u00d6rebro]] works to have: new fully enclosed cab; electric lighting; shortening of tender (to enable it to fit Swedish [[Turntable (rail)|turntables]]); renumbered Class G11 No. 1931.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Mothballed with No. 1930 in 1958. Inspected in 1972 by KWVR, arrived at [[Ingrow]] 1973. After three years of operations, withdrawn 1976. Heavy overhaul began in 1993, completed 2007. Renumbered to the number subsequent to the last UK BR owned WD 2-8-0 \u2013 No. 90733 \u2013 returned to traffic.<ref name=\"KWVR Rolling Stock Page\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kwvr.co.uk/guide/rolling-stock/the-fleet.html|title=The Fleet of Locomotives and Carriages|accessdate=1 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609113343/http://www.kwvr.co.uk/guide/rolling-stock/the-fleet.html|archivedate=9 June 2011}}</ref></small>\n\n<small>Boiler ticket originally due to expire in 2017 but later extended to April 2018. However, in December 2017 due to cracks being found in its boiler tubes, the decision was made to withdraw the loco as it was decided carrying out the repairs would not be economical with so little time left of the boiler ticket. As of July 2018 the engine is now being stripped down for overhaul.<ref name=\"kwvr.co.uk\">http://www.kwvr.co.uk/enthusiasts/steam-locomotives.html</ref></small>\n|}\n\n===Stored, static or on display===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! History and Current Status\n|-\n|No. 1704 \"Nunlow\"\n|[[Hudswell Clarke]]<br/>{{whyte|0-6-0|T}}\n|[[File:Hudswell Clarke Nunlow at Lafarge Hope Cement Works 1.jpg|175px]]\n|Green\n|<small>Built 1938 by [[Hudswell Clarke]] for the industrial railway connecting G&T Earle's cement works with the mainline at Hope on the ex-[[Midland Railway|Midland]] [[Sheffield]] to [[Manchester]] line.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Named ''Nunlow'' after a hill that stood on the works site. During the mid-1960s, role was taken over by diesel shunters. Taken to the [[Dinting Railway Centre]] in 1969, moved to KWVR in 1990.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Property of the Bahamas Locomotive Society, the locos boiler ticket expired in April 2018 and is now stored at Ingrow awaiting its turn in the overhaul queue.</small>\n|-\n|No. 5775\n|[[GWR 5700 Class|5700 Class]] {{whyte|0-6-0|PT}}\n|[[File:No. 5775 5700 Class 0-6-0PT.jpg|175px]]\n|[[The Railway Children (1970 film)|GN&SR Ochre]]\n|<small>Built for the Great Western Railway in September 1929 and worked at [[Neath]] shed in [[South Wales]]. At Nationalisation, it was at 87C shed \u2013 Danygraig, where it stayed until transfer to [[Carmarthen]] (87G) and finally to [[Pontypool]] Road (86G).<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Sold to [[London Transport (brand)|London Transport]] in July 1963,<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> numbered L89 and repainted in LT maroon livery. No. 5775 moved to KWVR in January 1970<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> where it starred as the locomotive that hauled the Old Gentleman's train in '[[The Railway Children (1970 film)|The Railway Children]]' film . In 2014, it was placed on loan to the [[National Railway Museum]] following cosmetic restoration at [[National Railway Museum Shildon|Shildon]] into its 'Railway Children' livery for the 45th anniversary of the film, returning to the line in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |work=Keighley and Worth Valley Railway |url=https://news.kwvr.co.uk/2016/11/30/november-ingrow-movements/ |title=Comings and Goings at Ingrow |publisher=Keighley & Worth Valley Railway|date=30 November 2016 |accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref> It is now on display in the museum at Oxenhope.</small>\n|-\n|No. 47279\n|[[London Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] {{whyte|0-6-0|T}} [[LMS Class 3F \"Jinty\" 0-6-0T|Class 3F \"Jinty\"]]\n|[[File:47279 at Keighley.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Unlined Black with early crest.\n|<small>Built by the LMS following a previous [[Midland Railway|Midland]] design, the Jinties were mainstay locomotives on the Worth Valley in its pre-preservation years. No. 7119 left the Vulcan Foundry in 1924.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Under the LMS 1934 renumbering scheme, it became No 7279 and finally at Nationalisation, it became 47279. This locomotive had an active life, and transferred between many areas and sheds in the LMS and later [[London Midland Region|LMR]]. It was bought by [[Woodham Brothers|Woodham Brothers Scrapyard]], and arrived at their scrapyard in [[Barry, Vale of Glamorgan|Barry]] in 1967. After 12 years rotting in the scrapyard, No 47279 arrived at Haworth in 1979. A very extensive restoration was carried out and 47279 entered service in February 1988.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> A further overhaul and return to service were completed in 2001 and 47279 gave ten years of reliable service before being retired from service on 23 July 2011 upon the expiry of its '10-year' boiler ticket. It is now on display in the museum at Oxenhope.</small>\n|-\n|No. 48431\n|LMS {{whyte|2-8-0}} [[LMS Class 8F 2-8-0|Class 8F]]\n|[[File:48431 LMS 2-8-0 Oxenhope Museum 1.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Unlined Black with late crest.\n|<small>Built in 1944. An example of [[Sir William Stanier|Sir William Stanier's]] 8F heavy freight locomotives. They played a very important role during [[World War II]] as they were built to keep the traffic moving in the United Kingdom and to support an Allied advance in Europe. In 1955 48431 was transferred to BR's Western region, being stationed successively at Bristol, Old Oak Common and Bath Green Part up to its withdrawal from service in 1964. After spending eight years at Barry scrapyard it arrived at Keighley in 1972 and was returned to service in 1975. A further overhaul was undertaken and the locomotive enjoyed another period of operation until it was withdrawn following the expiration of its boiler ticket at the end of 2000. It is now on display in the museum at Oxenhope, awaiting a full 10-yearly overhaul.\n\nIt is presently not paired with a tender as the Fowler tender it used prior to withdrawal was borrowed from the [[Midland Railway 3835 Class|Fowler 4F]] no 43924, this is now back in use with the 4F. Its own tender suffered from severe corrosion to the tender tank in multiple places and requires replacement before it can run again. It is to be fitted with the old tender tank from 45596 during its overhaul ([[LMS Jubilee Class 5596 Bahamas|45596]] received a new tender tank during its recent overhaul).</small>\n|-\n|No. 80002\n|BR {{whyte|2-6-4|T}} [[BR standard class 4 2-6-4T|Class 4MT]]\n|[[File:80002-BRClass4.JPG|175px]]\n|BR Lined Black with early crest.\n|<small>Part of the first batch of 10 to be ordered by the [[Scottish Region of British Railways|Scottish Region]] from [[Derby Works]], emerged in October 1952.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> Allocated to [[Motherwell TMD|Motherwell shed]] (66B); moved to Polmadie (66A). Transferred to Beattock shed (68D) in June 1962.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> After closure of branches around Beattock, it was moved back to Polmadie in April 1964, where it stayed until retirement in March 1967. After a short spell as a stationary steam heating boiler, moved to KWVR in 1969. Its boiler ticket expired on 22 August 2013 and was moved to the museum at Oxenhope for display in May 2014.</small>\n|-\n|No. 51218\n|[[L&YR Class 21|Class 21 \"Pug\"]]<br/>{{whyte|0-4-0|ST}}\n|[[File:L&YR Class 21 'Pug' No. 68 on display at Oxenhope.jpg|175px]]\n|BR unlined black with late crest\n|<small>Built in 1901 No. 68 represents the \"Pug\" class which were small locomotives designed for use in sharply curved sidings. Under LMS ownership it was numbered 11218 and under BR ownership it was numbered 51218. It was the first locomotive to arrive at Haworth in 1964, the same year that it was withdrawn from service in Wales and has since had several periods in steam where it has been seen in its BR guise as 51218 or its present L&Y guise as 68. It is currently awaiting overhaul which is planned to start once 752 is finished. Currently on display at Oxenhope, it was comestically restored for the 50th anniversary of the KWVR in 2018.</small>\n|-\n|No. 31 \"Hamburg\"\n|[[Hudswell Clarke]]<br/>{{whyte|0-6-0|T}}\n|[[File:Hudswell Clarke Hamburg in Oxenhope Museum.JPG|175px]]\n|Black.\n|<small>Built in 1903. \"Hamburg\" is an example of one of the Manchester Ship Canal \"short tanks\" which arrived at the railway in 1967. It has been featured in several television programs such as ''Sherlock Holmes''. \"Hamburg\" is now on display in the museum at Oxenhope, requiring a new inner firebox and a general overhaul.</small>\n|-\n|No. 118 \"Brussels\"\n|[[Hudswell Clarke]] [[Hunslet Austerity 0-6-0ST|\"Austerity\"]]<br/>{{whyte|0-6-0|ST}}\n|[[File:118 WD 0-6-0 ST Oxenhope Museum 1.jpg|175px]]\n|[[Longmoor Military Railway|LMR]] blue.\n|<small>Built in 1945. Requires a general overhaul.</small>\n|-\n|No. 2258 \"Tiny\"\n|[[Andrew Barclay Sons & Co.|Andrew Barclay]]<br/>{{whyte|0-4-0|ST}}\n|[[File:Andrew Barclay and Sons 'Tiny'.jpg|175px]]\n|Black.\n|<small>Built in 1949. On display at Ingrow West awaiting a general overhaul, owned by the Bahamas trust.</small>\n|-\n|\"Lord Mayor\"\n|[[Hudswell Clarke]]<br/>{{whyte|0-4-0|ST}}\n|[[File:Hudswell Clarke Lord Mayor.jpg|175px]]\n|Lined green.\n|<small>Built in 1893. On display at Ingrow West awaiting overhaul.</small>\n|}\n\n===Former Worth Valley Residents===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Type\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! History and Current Status\n|-\n|No. 67\n|[[Hudswell Clarke]] {{whyte|0-6-0|T}}\n|[[File:MSC No. 67 at the Middleton Railway.jpg|175px]]\n|N/A\n|<small>Currently located at [[Middleton Railway]] awaiting overhaul, it was also used in the 1970 film ''[[The Railway Children (1970 film)|The Railway Children]]'' where it was used as the engine which took the three children and their mother from London to Oakworth and it was also the engine which brought in the train that had the children's father on board.</small>\n|-\n|No. 7289 \"Fred\"\n|[[Hunslet Austerity 0-6-0ST|Hunslet Austerity]] {{whyte|0-6-0|ST}}\n|\n|N/A\n|<small>Currently located at [[Tyseley Locomotive Works]] awaiting restoration.</small>\n|-\n|No. 30072\n|[[SR Class USA|Class USA]] {{whyte|0-6-0|T}}\n|[[File:SR USA Class Worth Valley 72 at Ingrow West Museum.jpg|175px]]\n|KWVR Brown\n|<small>After World War II, the [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]] needed to replace ageing shunting engines at [[Southampton Docks]]. They decided to use the [[USATC]] built [[SR Class USA|USA tanks]]. No. 30072 started life at the [[Vulcan Iron Works#Pennsylvania.2C United States|Vulcan Iron Works]] in 1943 as works number 4446.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> After 4 years, the Southern Railway bought it and 14 others of its class renumbering it No. 72. At nationalisation, 30,000 was added to the number (as was customary for southern engines), and it stayed at Southampton. In 1962, its duties were taken over by diesel shunting engines and No. 30072 was moved to [[Guildford (Surrey) railway station#Motive Power Depot|Guildford (70C)]] shed.<ref name=\"KWVR Locos ATW\"/> On 9 July 1967, it was moved to Salisbury for storage, from where it was bought.</small>\n\n<small>When at the Keighley and Worth Valley Railway, it hauled the re-opening special with 41241. It operated as an oil-burning locomotive from 1976 to 1987.</small>\n\n<small>No. 30072 was purchased by Andy Booth (the current owner of [[L&YR Class 27]] no 1300) in August 2015 and is presently stored inside the [[Ribble Steam Railway]]'s museum awaiting a space in the workshop for its overhaul to commence. Once its overhaul is completed at the RSR it is planned to return on loan to the railway.<ref>{{cite web |work=Keighley and Worth Valley Railway |url=http://news.kwvr.co.uk/2015/08/25/30072-240815/ |title=USA Tank 30072 for 50th Anniversary Special? |publisher=Keighley & Worth Valley Railway|date=25 August 2015 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|No. 34092 [[Wells, Somerset|\"City of Wells\"]]\n|SR {{whyte|4-6-2}} [[SR West Country Class|West Country Class]]\n|[[File:34092 approaches Ais Gill summit.jpg|175px]]\n|BR lined green with early emblem.\n|<small>Built in March 1949, No. 34092 was a member of the final batch of 20 [[SR West Country and Battle of Britain classes|West Country Class]] locomotives ordered.<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p12\">{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=12}}</ref> It was based at [[Stewarts Lane|Stewarts Lane (73A)]] until it was moved to [[Salisbury railway station#Motive power depots|Salisbury (72B)]]. While at Stewarts Lane, it was named 'Wells' by the mayor of [[Wells, Somerset|Wells]] on 25 November 1949<ref name=\"Heavyside1996p12\" /> (changed to 'City of Wells', unique amongst the rest of its class which were named only after the town, city or region, in March 1950). No. 34092 was often called upon to haul the [[Golden Arrow (train)|Golden Arrow]] service and was further chosen to haul special trains for the visit of [[Bulganin]] and [[Khrushchev]], and [[Faisal II of Iraq|King Faisal II of Iraq]].</small>\n\n<small>Having covered {{convert|502864|mi}},<ref>{{harvnb|Heavyside|1996|p=13}}</ref> No. 34092 was sent to [[Woodham Brothers|Woodham's scrapyard]]. However, in 1971, it was bought by the KWVR and, after overhaul, was used throughout the 1980s both on the branch and on mainline excursions. A [[Giesl ejector]] was fitted in 1985. No. 34092 returned to service in August 2014 following an extensive overhaul. The locomotive is also planned to return to traffic on the mainline when funding is available to purchase the equipment needed for use on [[Network Rail]]. No. 34092 is now based at the [[East Lancashire Railway]] following sale.</small>\n|-\n|No. 45025\n|[[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0|LMS Black 5]] {{whyte|4-6-0}}\n|[[File:Black 5 no.5025 - geograph.org.uk - 511056.jpg|175px]]\n|LMS Lined Black\n|<small>Following withdrawal from service with [[British Rail|British Railways]] in 1968 which was later followed with an overhaul being undertaken at Hunslet in [[Leeds]] No. 45025 was moved by rail under it's own power to the Keighley and Worth Valley Railway becoming one of the two preserved black 5's to be based on the railway (the second engine being 45212). The engine was based at the K&WVR from 1968 until 1974 when the engine was re-allocated to the [[Strathspey Railway (preserved)|Strathspey Railway]] in [[Aviemore]], [[Scotland]].</small><ref>https://preservedbritishsteamlocomotives.com/45025-lms-45025-br-45025/ 45025 loco history</ref>\n\n<small>As of 2020 No. 45025 is presently undergoing an overhaul and is still based at the Strathspey Railway.</small>\n|-\n|No. [[LMS Royal Scot Class 6115 Scots Guardsman|46115 \"Scots Guardsman\"]]\n|[[LMS Royal Scot Class|LMS Royal Scot]] {{whyte|4-6-0}}\n|[[File:46115 - Scots Guardsman hauling the Scarborough Spar Express.jpg|175px]]\n|BR lined green with the late crest\n|<small>No. 46115 was based on the line for a while, but due to weight restrictions did not see much use. Departed the line in the 1970s for overhaul to mainline condition and was later painted into LMS Black. It was later purchased by its current owner David Smith and overhauled to modern mainline standard with its return to service being in 2008. Operational & mainline certified it is based at [[Carnforth MPD]].\n|-\n|No. 65894 (2392)\n|[[NER Class P3|LNER Class J27]] {{whyte|0-6-0}}\n|[[File:York Locomotive Yard an ex-NE Raven J27 0-6-0 geograph-2355868-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Unlined Black, Late Crest\n|<small>The engine is still owned by the [[North Eastern Locomotive Preservation Group]] and is currently based at the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]]. The loco returned to service in May 2018 following a 12-year overhaul inside both the NYMR's workshop as well as the NELPG's own workshop in Hopetown ([[Darlington]]).</small>\n|-\n|No. 69023\n|[[NER Class E1|LNER Class J72]] {{whyte|0-6-0|T}}\n|[[File:LNER J72 69023 Joem Bedale 06.07.14R edited-2.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Apple Green, Late Crest\n|<small>Owned by the North Eastern Locomotive Preservation Group and now based on the Wensleydale Railway but occasionally goes to the society's workshop in Darlington as well as visits to other railways across the UK. 69023's last overhaul started in 2005 and was completed in 2008. It is now undergoing another overhaul at Darlington.</small>\n\n<small>It even had a starring role in the BBC's 1968 TV production \"The Railway Children\".</small>\n|-\n|No. 1744\n|[[LNER N2]] {{whyte|0-6-2|T}}\n|[[File:GNR 1744 (6931087594).jpg|175px]]\n|Plain Black\n|<small>No. 1744 was purchased for preservation by the Gresley Society in October 1963, and moved from Doncaster Works to Haworth Colliery for storage. After steaming at the colliery, it was moved to the Keighley and Worth Valley railway where it gained fame by appearing as the Scots Flyer in ''[[The Railway Children (1970 film)|The Railway Children]]''. No. 1744 did little work after that as a boiler tube failure necessitated considerable boiler work. The Main Line Steam Trust eventually offered to undertake this work as the N2 was ideal for the Great Central Railway, and the locomotive moved to Quorn & Woodhouse on 21 November 1975. Currently undergoing overhaul at the [[North Norfolk Railway]].</small>\n|-\n|No. 68077\n|[[LNER Class J94]] {{whyte|0-6-0|ST}}\n|[[File:Harringay West, with ex-WD 0-6-0T geograph-2890663-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|175px]]\n|N/A\n|<small>Formerly based at the [[Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]] in the 1970s, but was withdrawn requiring vacuum brakes and steam heat fitting. It is now based at the [[Spa Valley Railway]] and undergoing an overhaul.</small>\n|}\n\n==Diesel locomotives and Multiple Units==\n\n===Operational===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! Current Status\n|-\n|No. D2511\n|BR 0-6-0 [[British Rail Class D2/12]]\n|[[File:Hudswell-Clarke 0-6-0 D2511, K&WVR, November 2012 Photo04 2 (9859813135).jpg|x175px|center]]\n|BR Green with wasp stripes.\n|<small>In use as the Carriage yard shunter at Oxenhope.</small>\n|-\n|No. 32 \"Huskisson\"\n|[[Mersey Docks and Harbour Board]] Diesel Mechanical 0-6-0\n|[[File:Hudswell Clarke Huskisson at Haworth.JPG|175px]]\n|Black\n|<small>Back in service for the 2014 Diesel Gala after a long delayed overhaul. Occasionally operates shunting duties where required.</small><ref>http://worthnews.wordpress.com/2014/05/14/2014-diesel-gala-6th-8th-june-full-line-up/</ref>\n|-\n|No. D0226 \"Vulcan\"\n|BR 0-6-0 [[British Rail D0226|Prototype EE shunter]]\n|[[File:D0226 Vulcan at Haworth.JPG|175px]]\n|BR Green.\n|<small>Used to operate the works train and occasional passenger service. </small>\n|- \n|No. 08266 (ex 13336)\n|BR 0-6-0 [[British Rail Class 08|Class 08]]\n|[[File:170202.134540. Haworth, KWVR Depot. Class 08.266.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Departmental Grey\n|<small>In use but restricted to Haworth yard duties as the locomotive is currently suffering from worn tyres. Appeared at 2008 diesel gala working shuttles between Keighley and Ingrow.</small>\n|-\n|No. 08993 \"Ashburnham\"\n|BR 0-6-0 [[British Rail Class 08|Class 08]]\n|[[File:08993 Castleton.jpg|x175px|center]]\n|EWS Maroon and Gold.\n|<small>Built in 1959 as No. D3759 and later 08592. The locomotive was later rebuilt with a cut down cab and body for use on the [[Burry Port and Gwendraeth Valley Railway]]. It was purchased by the KWVR in August 2015 as a replacement for No. 08266 and arrived in September that year. It returned to service following a light overhaul in June 2016. The loco is dual braked, making it useful for shunting air brake only vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |work=Keighley and Worth Valley Railway |url=http://news.kwvr.co.uk/2015/09/05/08993-class-08-shunter/ |title='New' Class 08 Shunter |publisher=Keighley & Worth Valley Railway |date=5 September 2015 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref></small>\n|-\n|No. 20031 (ex-D8031)\n|BR Bo-Bo [[British Rail Class 20|Class 20]]\n|[[File:Diesel Power at Oakworth Station - geograph.org.uk - 253039.jpg|175px]]\n|Railfreight Coal Sector 3 Tone Grey.\n|<small>Returned to traffic in September 2008 after a second main generator repair. Currently available for use.</small>\n|-\n|No. 25059 (ex-D5209)\n|BR Bo-Bo [[British Rail Class 25|Class 25]]\n|[[File:25059 Oxenhope Keighley and Worth Valley Railway.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Blue with full yellow ends.\n|<small>Built in 1963. Restored to traffic following bodywork repairs, mainly to cab floors. Operational. </small>\n|-\n|No. 37075\n|[[British Rail Class 37|Class 37]]\n|[[File:140612.115224. Haworth Depot. Class 37. 37075.jpg|175px]]\n|Railfreight Grey with full yellow ends.\n|<small>Built in 1962. Operational. The loco has two different types of nose end.</small>\n|-\n|Nos. 51803+51189\n|BR [[British Rail Class 101|Class 101]] unit.\n|[[File:Class 101 DMU arrives at Oxenhope.JPG|175px]]\n|BR Green with yellow warning panels.\n|<small>Returned to service in 2013 following restoration and now in regular use.</small>\n|-\n|Nos. 55811+51834 (144011)\n|BR [[British Rail Class 144|Class 144]] unit.\n|[[File:144011 at Hebden Bridge.jpg|175px]]\n|Northern Rail unbranded with yellow warning panels.\n|<small>Presently in service with [[Northern Trains|Northern]], will be preserved following withdrawal from service in August 2020.</small>\n|-\n|No. 79964\n|BR [[Waggon- und Maschinenbau GmbH Donauw\u00f6rth railbus|Waggon und Maschinenbau Railbus]]\n|[[File:Railbus 79964 at York Railfest.JPG|175px]]\n|BR Green with yellow warning panels.\n|<small>In regular use on morning diesel services.</small>\n|}\n\n===Out of service===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! Photograph\n! Livery\n! Current Status\n|-\n|No. 23 \"Merlin\"\n|[[Port of Bristol|Port of Bristol Authority]] Diesel Mechanical 0-6-0\n|[[File:No 23 Keighley and Worth Valley Railway.jpg|175px]]\n|Unlined Black.\n|<small>Previously in use at Oxenhope station as the carriage and wagon yard shunter, now withdrawn due to poor mechanical condition and stored at Haworth MPD until its turn for overhaul.</small>\n|-\n|Nos. 50928+51565\n|[[British Rail Class 108|Class 108]].\n|[[File:Class_108_at_Oxenhope.jpg|175px]]\n|BR Green (50928 has speed whiskers and 51565 has a yellow warning panel).\n|<small>Was in regular use on morning diesel services from the 1990s until 2013 when it was withdrawn for a well deserved overhaul which is now in progress. </small>\n|-\n|No. 79962\n|BR [[British Rail Railbuses|Waggon und Maschinenbau Railbus]] (See 7)\n|~\n|BR lined green with wasp stripes.\n|<small>Undergoing a heavy overhaul in the Vintage Carriage Trust's shed at Ingrow, the engines restoration has been finished.</small>\n|}\n\n==Carriages and wagons==\n\n=== Normal Service Stock ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! History and Current Status\n! Livery\n! Photograph\n|-\n|1013\n|BR Mk 1 Restaurant Second Open\n|built 1951\n|BR Maroon\n|[[File:161007.125740. Oxenhope KWVR.jpg|175px|]]\n|-\n|46157\n|BR Mk 1 Second\n|built 1954\n|BR Maroon\n|[[File:Keighley, No.46157.jpg|175px|]]~\n|-\n|43003\n|BR Mk 1 non-gangwayed Lavatory Composite\n|built 1954\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|43128\n|BR Mk 1 Brake Second\n|built 1954\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|43145\n|BR Mk 1 Brake Second\n|built 1955\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|43345\n|BR Mk1 Brake Second\n|Built 1955 \n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|48011\n|BR Mk 1 Second Lavatory Open\n|built 1955\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|48018\n|BR Mk 1 Second Lavatory Open\n|built 1955\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|80591\n|BR Mk 1 Gangwayed Full Brake\n|built 1955\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|43345\n|BR Mk 1 Brake Second\n|built 1955\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|4304\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open (now converted to Buffet Car)\n|built 1956\n|BR Maroon\n|[[File:Oxenhope. 13th October 2006.jpg|175px|]]\n|-\n|4306\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1956\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|4467\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1956\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|9273\n|BR Mk 1 Brake Second Open\n|built 1956\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|4588\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open (Now converted to Bar Car for dining trains)\n|built 1956\n|Pullman Umber & Cream\n|~\n|-\n|4774\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1957\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|4840\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1959\n|BR Maroon\n|[[File:161007.161606. Keighley KWVR.jpg|175px|]]\n|-\n|4900\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1960\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|1963\n|BR Mk 1 Unclassed Restaurant Car (later RK)\n|built 1960\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|1836\n|BR Mk 1 Restaurant Miniature Buffet\n|built 1960\n|BR Maroon\n|[[File:13th October 2006. E1836.jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|4955\n|BR Mk 1 Tourist Second Open\n|built 1961\n|BR Maroon\n|~\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Vintage carriages and carriages for special use ===\nThe railway has amassed a large collection of Vintage Carriages over the years. Some are used to carry passengers on specially selected open days.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! History and Current Status\n! Livery\n! Photograph\n|-\n|1867\n|GNR\n|Incomplete\n|N/A\n|~\n|-\n|154\n|MSLR Tricomposite, luggage compartment\n|<small>Built 1876. On display.</small>\n|Great Central Railway.\n|[[File:MSLR Luggage Compartment No. 176.jpg|175px]] \n|-\n|1507\n|LYR 6 wheel 5 compartment Third\n|<small>Built 1882. Uses underframes of LMS 32988 BGZ built 1938. Operational.</small>\n|L&YR lined light over dark brown.\n|[[File:B-UK-F-LUX 2012 469 Keighley - Worth Valley Railway (7811898760).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|358\n|MR 6 wheel Composite\n|<small>Built 1886. Undergoing restoration.</small>\n|Railway Children red and white.\n|[[File:Museum rollingstock, Oxenhope (geograph 5905729).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|589\n|GNR 6 wheel Brake Third\n|<small>Built 1888. Operational.</small>\n|Varnished teak.\n|[[File:Great Northern Railway six-wheeled Brake Third \u2018589\u2019 (20521082876).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|279\n|LYR 4 compartment First\n|<small>Body only, built 1894. Running on under-frames from LMS 33007 BGZ (built 1940). Operational.</small>\n|L&YR lined light over dark brown.\n|~\n|-\n|2856\n|GNR Composite Lavatory Brake\n|<small>Built 1898. On display.</small>\n|GNR varnished teak.\n|[[File:GNR 2856 Carriage (1569668407).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|1661\n|NER Clerestory Saloon\n|<small>Built 1904. Operational.</small>\n|LNER varnished teak.\n|[[File:NER Inspection Saloon No.1661 (LNER No.21661) (6966750690).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|135\n|LYR Director's Saloon\n|<small>Built 1908. On display.</small>\n|L&YR lined light over dark brown.\n|[[File:Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Saloon \u2018No2\u2019 (20524424515).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|1474\n|LYR Hughes taper-end Brake\n|<small>Built 1910. Operational.</small>\n|L&YR lined light over dark brown..\n|[[File:LYR 1474 Hughes taper-end Brake Third (L&YR) built 1910.jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|427\n|Metropolitan 'Dreadnought' Brake\n|<small>Built 1910. Operational.</small>\n|London Transport brown.\n|[[File:160731.021. Oakworth, KWVR.jpg|175px|.]]\n|-\n|47\n|LYR Blackpool Club Car\n|<small>Built 1912. Running on BR 46145 Mk1 Second (built 1954) under-frames. Operational.</small>\n|L&YR lined black and brown.\n|[[File:Rth LYR 47 KWVR Oxenhope 30.06.13.jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|465\n|Metropolitan 'Dreadnought' 9-compartment third\n|<small>Built 1919. Operational.</small>\n|London Transport brown.\n|[[File:Metropolitan Railway Dreadnought Coach (17190013338).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|509\n|Metropolitan 'Dreadnought' 7-compartment First\n|<small>Built 1923. Operational.</small>\n|Metropolitan Railway lined varnished teak.\n|[[File:Dreadnoughts at North Weald July 2013.JPG|175px]]\n|-\n|3554\n|SR 'Matchboard' Continental Brake third\n|<small>Built 1924. Operational.</small>\n|BR carmine and cream.\n|[[File:SR Matchboard Continental Brake third 3554 at Keighley.JPG|175px]]\n|-\n|8761\n|LMS CK\n|<small>Built 1924 (later World War II Ambulance Car). Awaiting restoration.</small>\n|\n|~\n|-\n|84\n|Pullman LNER 255 Pullman Parlour Third \"Mary\"\n|<small>Built 1931. Operational.</small>\n|Pullman umber and cream.\n|[[File:Pullman LNER 255 CAR NO 84 Pullman Parlour Third built 1931.jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|83\n|Pullman LNER 261 Pullman Parlour Third \"Anne\"\n|<small>Built 1931. Operational.</small>\n|Pullman umber and cream.\n|~\n|-\n|4247\n|LNER Gresley BG(P) (Gangwayed Full Brake/Pigeon Van)\n|<small>Built 1938. On display.</small>\n|BR maroon.\n|[[File:B-UK-F-LUX 2012 388 Keighley - Worth Valley Railway (7811266224).jpg|175px]]\n|-\n|12066\n|LMS 9-compartment Third\n|<small>Built 1938. Awaiting overhaul.</small>\n|BR lined maroon.\n|~\n|-\n|31082\n|LMS Gangwayed Full Brake\n|<small>Built 1940. Operational.</small>\n|BR lined maroon.\n|~\n|-\n|1517\n|SR 4 wheel PMVY (Parcels & Miscellaneous Van)\n|<small>Built 1947. Used as a store.</small>\n|Maroon.\n|~\n|-\n|12244\n|LMS 9 compartment Third\n|<small>Built 1950. Awaiting overhaul.</small>\n|BR lined maroon.\n|~\n|-\n|1469\n|SR Bulleid Third Open\n|<small>Built 1950. Operational.</small>\n|BR carmine and cream.\n|[[File:SR Bulleid Third Open 1469 at Oxenhope.JPG|175px]]\n|}\n\n=== Freight Wagons ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Number & Name\n! Description\n! History and Current Status\n! Livery\n! Photograph\n|-\n|640\n|LMS MTY (4 wheel Milk Tank) (later, MTZ)\n|built 1928\n|\n|~\n|-\n|12270\n|SR 6-PAN EMU TFK\n|built 1935 (underframe only)\n|\n|~\n|-\n|1125\n|SR 4 wheel PMVY (Parcels & Miscellaneous Van)\n|built 1936\n|\n|~\n|-\n|1304\n|SR 4 wheel PMVY\n|built 1939 (now u/f only, as crane runner)\n|\n|~\n|-\n|1334\n|LNER CCTY (4 wheel Covered Carriage Truck)\n|built 1950\n|\n|~\n|-\n|1550\n|SR 4 wheel PMVY (Parcels & Miscellaneous Van)\n|built 1951\n|\n|~\n|-\n|37311\n|LMS 4 wheel CCT (Covered Carriage Truck)\n|built 1952\n|\n|~\n|-\n|87582\n|BR Blue Spot 4-wheel Fish Van\n|built 1960\n|\n|~\n|-\n|87706\n|BR Blue Spot 4-wheel Fish Van\n|built 1960\n|\n|~\n|-\n|87948\n|BR Blue Spot 4 wheel Fish Van\n|built 1960\n|\n|~\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other Rolling Stock==\nThe railway owns three rail mounted [[crane (railroad)|cranes]]: a 10T Grafton steam P-Way crane, a 15T Taylor Hubbard diesel P-Way Crane and an ex LMS 45T steam breakdown crane. Currently only the 15T Taylor Hubbard crane and the Grafton steam train are available for use.  Furthermore, there are a variety of wagons used by the civil engineering department, largely at either Oakworth of Ingrow West.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Rolling stock of the Keighley and Worth Valley Railway}}\n* [http://www.kwvr.co.uk/  Keighley and Worth Valley Railway website]\n* [http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org Ingrow Museum of Rail Travel \u2013 Vintage Carriages Trust]\n* [http://www.bahamas45596.co.uk Ingrow Loco Museum \u2013 Bahamas Locomotive Society]\n* [http://www.britishrailways1960.co.uk/NERS76.html  British Railways in 1960 \u2013 Keighley to Oxenhope]\n* [http://www.lyrtrust.org.uk/  Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Trust website]\n\n[[Category:Lists of locomotives and rolling stock preserved on heritage railways in England|Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]]\n[[Category:Keighley and Worth Valley Railway|*]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolling_stock_of_the_Keighley_and_Worth_Valley_Railway"}
